{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657363"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:27:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:27:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19586"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19586"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.2,0.23,0.2,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86072"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12357"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70337"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6816"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29516"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86072"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents for investigation of progressive dysphagia. A computed tomography scan of the chest is performed to evaluate for external compression of the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows an axial slice through the thorax at the level of the posterior mediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is indicated by the red arrow?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oesophagus","Descending thoracic aorta","Left lower lobe bronchus","Azygos vein","Left inferior pulmonary vein"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe structure indicated by the red arrow is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft inferior pulmonary vein\u003C/strong\u003E, which drains the lower left lobe of the lung. It lies adjacent to the descending thoracic aorta in the posterior mediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be distinguished by their characteristic anatomical positions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E appears as a small, collapsed tubular structure anterior to the thoracic aorta and can be compressed by surrounding structures causing dysphagia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edescending thoracic aorta\u003C/strong\u003E appears as a round, contrast-filled structure immediately anterior to the vertebral bodies. Thoracic aortic aneurysms can cause dysphagia by compressing the oesophagus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft lower lobe bronchus\u003C/strong\u003E appears as an air-filled tubular structure with thick walls and is more lateral in position\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eazygos vein\u003C/strong\u003E is located on the right side of the vertebral column and appears as a small, contrast-filled structure\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these anatomical relationships is clinically relevant when evaluating causes of dysphagia. Mediastinal masses, including enlarged lymph nodes, retrosternal goitre, and vascular anomalies, can compress the oesophagus leading to difficulty swallowing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The left inferior pulmonary vein drains the lower left lobe of the lung and lies adjacent to the descending thoracic aorta.","The posterior mediastinum contains key anatomical structures including the oesophagus, thoracic aorta, azygos vein, and pulmonary vessels.","Anatomical knowledge of the posterior mediastinum is crucial for evaluating causes of dysphagia."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70337"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19586"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21631"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21631"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/myrp8FlVlMX2zFKI343q1qGyKnrXlk.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/myrp8FlVlMX2zFKI343q1qGyKnrXlk.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":539,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70337"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-19T08:14:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-19T08:14:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12357"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86072"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":